-- Japan, China, India, Philippines, Thailand: Asian Bonds, Currency Preview
-- B y   Y u m i   T e s o
-- 2010-10-18T22:13:27Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-18/japan-china-india-philippines-thailand-asian-bonds-currency-preview.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary Yoshito Sengoku and Finance
Minister Yoshihiko Noda will hold media briefings after a
Cabinet meeting in the morning. Sengoku will have another press
briefing at 4 p.m. in Tokyo. The Cabinet Office will release its
monthly economic report after the morning meeting.  Trade Minister Akihiro Ohata will speak at the Foreign
Correspondents’ Club of Japan from around 11:45 a.m. in Tokyo.  The yield on the 0.8 percent government bond due September
2020 was at 0.87 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co.,
the nation’s largest interdealer debt broker. The yen traded at
81.28 per dollar at 7:07 a.m. in Tokyo.  China: The People’s Bank of China will sell 43 billion yuan
($6.47 billion) of one-year debt today. Export-Import Bank of
China will auction 10 billion yuan of two-year bonds.  The yield on the 2.53 percent note due June 2015 was 2.73
percent. The yuan was at 6.6441.  India: The government plans to raise as much as 60 billion
rupees ($1.36 billion) selling treasury bills at an auction
tomorrow. It will offer 40 billion rupees of 91-day notes and 20
billion rupees of 364-day securities.  The yield on the 7.80 percent bond due May 2020 was 8.09
percent. The rupee was at 44.3650.  Philippines: Balance of payments data for September is due
today. The balance was $40 million the previous month, according
to central bank data.  The budget balance for September may be released today. The
country reported a surplus of 1.3 billion pesos ($30 million) in
August.  The yield on the 6.125 percent debt due September 2020 was
5.94 percent, according to Philippine Dealing & Exchange Corp.
The peso was at 43.278 per dollar.  Thailand: The Bank of Thailand will sell a total of 61
billion baht ($2 billion) of 28-, 91- and 182-day bills. The
central bank will also offer 50 billion baht of two-year notes.  The yield on the 3.625 percent note due May 2015 was 2.46
percent. The baht was at 29.89.  To contact the reporter responsible for this story:
Yumi Teso in Bangkok at 
